This is with pyglfw 1.3.3 on Linux. The _load_library call in  glfw.py uses a fixed set of paths that it searches for the GLFW shared lib. Unfortunately, I don't have GLFW3 installed system-wide as the available Debian package on jessie is a bit old. So I compiled and installed the latest GLFW3 in a custom location (/software/glfw/3.2.1 in this case), but I can't direct pyglfw to get the shared lib from there without hacking glfw.py.

Here's an updated excerpt of glfw.py, starting around line 150, to make it search the paths in LD_LIBRARY_PATH as well:

if sys.platform == 'win32':
    # only try glfw3.dll on windows
    try:
        _glfw = ctypes.CDLL('glfw3.dll')
    except OSError:
        _glfw = None
else:
    search_paths = [
        '', 
        '/usr/lib64', '/usr/local/lib64',
        '/usr/lib', '/usr/local/lib',
        '/run/current-system/sw/lib',
        '/usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/'
    ]
    
    if 'LD_LIBRARY_PATH' in os.environ:
        search_paths.extend(os.environ['LD_LIBRARY_PATH'].split(':'))
        
    _glfw = _load_library(['glfw', 'glfw3'], ['.so', '.dylib'],
                          search_paths, _glfw_get_version)

Somewhat related to #356 but more specific to PCAN.

Any interest in some error-specific exceptions?  I just wrote up this generator to create an enumeration (`enum.IntFlag`) of errors as well as individual exceptions for each (non-composite) error.  It also parses the comments from the source, but maybe that should be skipped in favor of calling the pcan interface for getting text for an error number.

I thought it would be nice to keep the source code modification to a minimum, but this could instead be a source generation script if we want real code in a file to provide these exceptions.

https://repl.it/@altendky/python-can-pcanbasic-exceptions-and-error-enumeration

<details> <summary>Click to expand</summary>

```python3
import enum
import inspect

import PCANBasic


def generate(module, prefix):
    all_errors = {
        name[len(prefix):]: getattr(module, name)
        for name in dir(module)
        if name.startswith(prefix)
    }

    compound_errors = {
        name: value
        for name, value in all_errors.items()
        if sum(int(c) for c in '{:b}'.format(value)) > 1
    }
    # print(compound_errors)

    simple_errors = {
        name: value
        for name, value in all_errors.items()
        if name not in compound_errors
    }

    Errors = enum.Flag('Errors', all_errors)

    source = inspect.getsourcelines(module)[0]
    comments = {
        getattr(Errors, line.partition('=')[0].strip()[len(prefix):]): line.partition('#')[2].strip()
        for line in source
        if line.startswith(prefix)
    }

    def create_exception(error):
        comment = comments[error]

        def __init__(self):
            print('yep, it is set.', comment)
            self.args = (comment,)

        return type(
            error.name + 'Error',
            (Exception,),
            {
                '__init__': __init__,
            },
        )

    exceptions = {
        getattr(Errors, name): create_exception(getattr(Errors, name))
        for name in simple_errors
    }

    return Errors, comments, exceptions

Errors, comments, exceptions = generate(
    module=PCANBasic,
    prefix='PCAN_ERROR_',
)
```
</details>

